<section class="band">
    <div class="wrap">
        <div class="head">
            <span class="eyebrow">How sensitive information leaves</span>
            <h2>It rarely walks in. It walks out — with someone who had the login.</h2>
            <p class="lede">In the documented record of trade-secret and client-data loss, the threat is seldom an outside attacker. It's a contractor, a departing employee, or a partner who left before anyone checked what they still held.</p>
        </div>
        <ul class="vectors">
            <li><b>Work on personal accounts</b> — strategy, creative, and client files living in a contractor's own Drive, with no copy on your systems.</li>
            <li><b>Devices left logged in</b> — a shared office iPad, a demo laptop, a phone still signed into executive mail.</li>
            <li><b>Communications</b> — leadership conversations on consumer apps with no governance and no record of who can still read them.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="vectors-close">No breach is needed when the access was issued and never withdrawn.</p>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="band">
    <div class="wrap">
        <div class="head"><span class="eyebrow">How it actually happens</span></div>
        <div class="vigs">
            <article class="vig">
                <h3>The contractor whose Drive held everything</h3>
                <p>A marketing contractor worked with the company for two years, running everything through her own Google account because, at the start, that was the simplest way to share. Every brief, every campaign, every creative file lived in a folder she owned. When the contract ended, the company reached for its work and found it had none — three years of strategy and client data sat in an account that was never theirs. She wasn't malicious. She simply had all of it.</p>
            </article>
            <article class="vig">
                <h3>The iPad that was still logged in</h3>
                <p>The tablet lived in the conference room, used for demos and the occasional presentation — company property, nobody's in particular. What no one remembered was that it was still signed into an executive's accounts from a setup months earlier. Anyone who picked it up between meetings held the keys to leadership mail and shared files, with no password to ask for and no record that they'd looked.</p>
            </article>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="band">
    <div class="wrap">
        <div class="head">
            <span class="eyebrow">What we found</span>
        </div>
        <div class="vigs vigs--outcome">
            <article class="vig vig--outcome">
                <div class="vig-field" aria-hidden="true"></div>
                <h3>Seven things the handover checklist had missed</h3>
                <p>The CEO came to us ahead of a sensitive negotiation — a deal large enough that she wanted the company's security posture examined before it began. A key employee had departed six weeks earlier; the handover had been thorough, she believed. What an HR checklist doesn't cover is everything a competent employee does to make their own work easier. We found seven live access points: a shared folder link that survived the password reset; an app integration authorised at the account level, not the password level; a demo iPad in the conference room, still signed in to executive mail. The former employee's knowledge of the company stopped at the date of the engagement.</p>
            </article>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

